{"title_page": "George Guthridge", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=May 2014}}\n\n'''George Guthridge''' (born 1948) is an American author and educator. He has published over 70 short stories and five [[novels]] and has been acclaimed for his successes teaching writing and critical/creative thinking. In 1997 he and coauthor Janet Berliner won the Bram Stoker Award for the Year's Best Horror Novel.\n\n==Early life and education==\nGuthridge earned a B.A. in English from [[Portland State University]] in 1970,<ref name=resume>{{cite web|url=http://georgeguthridge.com/assets/Guthridge_resume.pdf|work=George Guthridge|title=Resum\u00e9|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190913212921/http://georgeguthridge.com/assets/Guthridge_resume.pdf|archive-date=September 13, 2019|access-date=September 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and a [[Master of Fine Arts]] in creative writing from the [[University of Montana]].<ref name=resume/> He earned a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] from the [[University of Alaska Fairbanks]] but did most of his doctoral work at [[Arizona State University]] in 2010.<ref name=resume/>\n\n== Speculative fiction ==\nIn the mid-1970s, Guthridge was teaching [[English studies|English]] at [[Loras College]]. A colleague in the department had received a [[grant (money)|grant]] to attend a [[science fiction convention]] in [[Milwaukee]], but was unable to attend, so Guthridge went instead (\"because Milwaukee is famous for beer\"), although he confesses that at that time he despised [[science fiction]] and [[fantasy]]. At the convention, Guthridge met [[George R. R. Martin]], who persuaded him to give [[speculative fiction]] a second look, and to write in the field himself. \"George changed my life, he really did,\" Guthridge says. \"Not just because he opened doors for me, but he opened this whole vista of sci-fi and fantasy and horror that I never would've gotten into.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/local/kyle-munson/2014/05/21/game-thrones-series-ex-iowa-professor-wrote-kyle-munson/2303526/}}</ref> In turn, Guthridge later helped Martin find a job at [[Clarke University|Clarke College]]. (Martin had been operating [[chess tournaments]] to supplement his writing income, but \"wasn't making enough money to stay alive,\" says Guthridge.)<ref>[http://www.press-citizen.com/story/entertainment/go-iowa-city/2014/05/23/westeros-iowa/9517663/ Munson, Kyle. \"Before Westeros, there was Iowa\" ''[[Iowa City Press-Citizen]]'' May 23, 2014]</ref> Guthridge has been a finalist for the [[Hugo Award]] and twice for the [[Nebula Award]] for [[science fiction]] and fantasy. In 1998 he and coauthor, [[Janet Berliner]], won the [[Bram Stoker Award]] for the year's best horror novel.\n\n== \"The Kids from Nowhere\" ==\nGuthridge is also known for having coached [[The Kids from Nowhere|ten students]] from the [[Siberian Yupik Eskimo]] village of [[Gambell, Alaska]], on blizzard-swept [[St. Lawrence Island]] in the [[Bering Sea]], to national championships in academics. They became the only [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] team ever to do that\u2014and they did it twice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thekidsfromnowhere.com/|title=YourWebHosting Login|website=www.thekidsfromnowhere.com}}</ref> Guthridge is the author of ''The Kids from Nowhere: The Story Behind the Arctic Educational Miracle'', published by Alaska Northwest Books in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gacpc.com/|title=HugeDomains.com - Gacpc.com is for sale (Gacpc)|website=www.gacpc.com}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n'''Novels'''\n*The Madagascar Manifesto (omnibus) (2002)<sup>1</sup> \n*Children of the Dusk (1997)<sup>1</sup> Bram Stoker Award Winner\n*Child of the Journey (1996)<sup>1</sup> \n*The Bloodletter (1994)\n*[[Child of the Light (novel)|Child of the Light]] (1991)<sup>1</sup>\n*The Death Mask of Pancho Villa (1987)<sup>2</sup>\n\n'''Nonfiction'''\n*The Kids from Nowhere (2006)\n\n'''Selected Short Fiction'''\n*The Bridge (2011)\n*Katoey (2008)<sup>3</sup>\n*Nine Whispered Opinions Regarding the Alaskan Secession (2004)\n*The Silence of Phii Krasue (2000)\n*Mister Pigman (1999)\n*Something's Got to Give (1999)<sup>1</sup>\n*Notes Toward a Rumpled Stillskin (1997)\n*Chin Oil (1997)\n*Mirror of Lop Nor (1995) \n*The I of the Eye of the Worm (1997)<sup>1</sup> \n*Maskal (1996)<sup>1</sup>\n*The Faliksotra (1995) <sup>1</sup>  \n*Inyanga (1995)<sup>1</sup> \n*Song of the Shofar (1994)<sup>1</sup> \n*The Macaw (1994)<sup>4</sup>\n*The Tower (1994) \n*Snowcoil (1993)\n*Exhibition (1988)\n*Philatelist (1988)\n*Evolutions (1988)\n*Recession (1987)\n*See the Station Master (1984)\n*Memory's Noose (1984)<sup>4</sup> \n*Legacy (1983)<sup>5</sup>\n*Champion of the World (1982)<sup>4</sup> \n*Triangle (1982)<sup>5</sup>\n*The Child (1982)\n*The Quiet (1982)\n*Blackmail (1982)\n*Taken on Faith (1982)\n*Pinnacle (1982)\n*Ishbar, the Trueborn (1981)\n*Jahratta Dki (1980)\n*Oregon (1979)\n*Warship (1979)<sup>6</sup>\n*The Exiled, the Hunted (1977)\n*Dolls' Demise (1976)\n     <sup>1</sup> with Janet Berliner\n     <sup>2</sup> with Carol Gaskins\n     <sup>3</sup> with Blythe Ayne\n     <sup>4</sup> with Steve Perry\n     <sup>5</sup> with Dianne Thompson\n     <sup>6</sup> with George R.R. Martin\n\n==Writing Awards==\n*1982 - Finalist, Nebula Award, \"The Quiet\" (science fiction short story)\n*1982 - Finalist, Hugo Award, \"The Quiet\" (science fiction short story)\n*1994 - Finalist, Nebula Award, \"The Mirror of Lop Nor\" (fantasy novelette)\n*1997 - Co-Winner, Bram Stoker Award, Year's Best Horror Novel (with Janet Berliner)\n*2007 - Finalist, Benjamin Franklin Award, Year's Best Book about Education, The Kids from Nowhere\n*2013 - First Place, Las Vegas International Film Festival, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n*2013 - First Place, Moondance International Film Festival, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n*2013 - First Place, Silent River International Film Festival, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n*2013 - First Place, New Hampshire International Film Festival, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n*2013 - Finalist, Portland International Film Festival, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n*2013 - Second Place, Kay Snow Writing Competition, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n\n==Educational Awards and Achievements==\n*1984 Future Problem Solving National Coach of the Year\n*1988 First Alaskan to be awarded Christa McAuliffe Fellowship\n*1990 Named (Simon & Schuster, Inc.) as one of America's top 78 teachers\n*1993 Profiled (Delacorte Press) as one of world's top educators\n*1996 Fulbright Scholar: Trained professors in the Caribbean \n*2001 Co-recipient, Alaska's first Distance Educator of the Year Award\n*2010 University of Alaska Fairbanks Exemplary Service Award\n*2013 University of Alaska Fairbanks Outstanding Faculty Advisor Award\n*2015 Professor Emeritus, University of Alaska Fairbanks\n*2018 Teaching Recognition Award, University of Maryland University College\n*2019 Finalist, Stanley J. Drazek Award for Teaching Excellence, University of Maryland University College\n\nGuthridge also helped develop the Rural Alaska Honors Institute (RAHI). It has become one of the nation's top college preparatory programs for Native Americans. Over 2000 of its graduates have gone on to college success, including at such institutions as Harvard, Dartmouth, Yale, Norte Dame, Stanford, Berkeley, West Point, Annapolis, and the Air Force Academy.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bram Stoker Award for Best Novel]]\n*[[Time Machine (book series)]]\n*[[Nebula Award for Best Short Story]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{isfdb name|id=George_Guthridge|name=George Guthridge}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guthridge, George}}\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American educators]]\n[[Category:American fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:American horror writers]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Portland State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Alaska Fairbanks alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Montana alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=May 2014}}\n\n'''George Guthridge''' (born 1948) is an American author and educator. He has published over 70 short stories and five [[novels]] and has been acclaimed for his successes teaching writing and critical/creative thinking. In 1997 he and coauthor Janet Berliner won the Bram Stoker Award for the Year's Best Horror Novel.\n\n==Early life and education==\nGuthridge earned a B.A. in English from [[Portland State University]] in 1970,<ref name=resume>{{cite web|url=http://georgeguthridge.com/assets/Guthridge_resume.pdf|work=George Guthridge|title=Resum\u00e9|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190913212921/http://georgeguthridge.com/assets/Guthridge_resume.pdf|archive-date=September 13, 2019|access-date=September 13, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and a [[Master of Fine Arts]] in creative writing from the [[University of Montana]].<ref name=resume/> He earned a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] from the [[University of Alaska Fairbanks]] but did most of his doctoral work at [[Arizona State University]] in 2010.<ref name=resume/>\n\n== Speculative fiction ==\nIn the mid-1970s, Guthridge was teaching [[English studies|English]] at [[Loras College]]. A colleague in the department had received a [[grant (money)|grant]] to attend a [[science fiction convention]] in [[Milwaukee]], but was unable to attend, so Guthridge went instead (\"because Milwaukee is famous for beer\"), although he confesses that at that time he despised [[science fiction]] and [[fantasy]]. At the convention, Guthridge met [[George R. R. Martin]], who persuaded him to give [[speculative fiction]] a second look, and to write in the field himself. \"George changed my life, he really did,\" Guthridge says. \"Not just because he opened doors for me, but he opened this whole vista of sci-fi and fantasy and horror that I never would've gotten into.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/local/kyle-munson/2014/05/21/game-thrones-series-ex-iowa-professor-wrote-kyle-munson/2303526/}}</ref> In turn, Guthridge later helped Martin find a job at [[Clarke University|Clarke College]]. (Martin had been operating [[chess tournaments]] to supplement his writing income, but \"wasn't making enough money to stay alive,\" says Guthridge.)<ref>[http://www.press-citizen.com/story/entertainment/go-iowa-city/2014/05/23/westeros-iowa/9517663/ Munson, Kyle. \"Before Westeros, there was Iowa\" ''[[Iowa City Press-Citizen]]'' May 23, 2014]</ref> Guthridge has been a finalist for the [[Hugo Award]] and twice for the [[Nebula Award]] for [[science fiction]] and fantasy. In 1998 he and coauthor, [[Janet Berliner]], won the [[Bram Stoker Award]] for the year's best horror novel.\n\n== \"The Kids from Nowhere\" ==\nGuthridge is also known for having coached [[The Kids from Nowhere|ten students]] from the [[Siberian Yupik Eskimo]] village of [[Gambell, Alaska]], on blizzard-swept [[St. Lawrence Island]] in the [[Bering Sea]], to national championships in academics. They became the only [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]] team ever to do that\u2014and they did it twice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thekidsfromnowhere.com/|title=YourWebHosting Login|website=www.thekidsfromnowhere.com}}</ref> Guthridge is the author of ''The Kids from Nowhere: The Story Behind the Arctic Educational Miracle'', published by Alaska Northwest Books in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gacpc.com/|title=HugeDomains.com - Gacpc.com is for sale (Gacpc)|website=www.gacpc.com}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n'''Novels'''\n*The Madagascar Manifesto (omnibus) (2002)<sup>1</sup> \n*Children of the Dusk (1997)<sup>1</sup> Bram Stoker Award Winner\n*Child of the Journey (1996)<sup>1</sup> \n*The Bloodletter (1994)\n*[[Child of the Light (novel)|Child of the Light]] (1991)<sup>1</sup>\n*The Death Mask of Pancho Villa (1987)<sup>2</sup>\n\n'''Nonfiction'''\n*The Kids from Nowhere (2006)\n\n'''Selected Short Fiction'''\n*The Bridge (2011)\n*Katoey (2008)<sup>3</sup>\n*Nine Whispered Opinions Regarding the Alaskan Secession (2004)\n*The Silence of Phii Krasue (2000)\n*Mister Pigman (1999)\n*Something's Got to Give (1999)<sup>1</sup>\n*Notes Toward a Rumpled Stillskin (1997)\n*Chin Oil (1997)\n*Mirror of Lop Nor (1995) \n*The I of the Eye of the Worm (1997)<sup>1</sup> \n*Maskal (1996)<sup>1</sup>\n*The Faliksotra (1995) <sup>1</sup>  \n*Inyanga (1995)<sup>1</sup> \n*Song of the Shofar (1994)<sup>1</sup> \n*The Macaw (1994)<sup>4</sup>\n*The Tower (1994) \n*Snowcoil (1993)\n*Exhibition (1988)\n*Philatelist (1988)\n*Evolutions (1988)\n*Recession (1987)\n*See the Station Master (1984)\n*Memory's Noose (1984)<sup>4</sup> \n*Legacy (1983)<sup>5</sup>\n*Champion of the World (1982)<sup>4</sup> \n*Triangle (1982)<sup>5</sup>\n*The Child (1982)\n*The Quiet (1982)\n*Blackmail (1982)\n*Taken on Faith (1982)\n*Pinnacle (1982)\n*Ishbar, the Trueborn (1981)\n*Jahratta Dki (1980)\n*Oregon (1979)\n*Warship (1979)<sup>6</sup>\n*The Exiled, the Hunted (1977)\n*Dolls' Demise (1976)\n     <sup>1</sup> with Janet Berliner\n     <sup>2</sup> with Carol Gaskins\n     <sup>3</sup> with Blythe Ayne\n     <sup>4</sup> with Steve Perry\n     <sup>5</sup> with Dianne Thompson\n     <sup>6</sup> with George R.R. Martin\n\n==Writing Awards==\n*1982 - Finalist, Nebula Award, \"The Quiet\" (science fiction short story)\n*1982 - Finalist, Hugo Award, \"The Quiet\" (science fiction short story)\n*1994 - Finalist, Nebula Award, \"The Mirror of Lop Nor\" (fantasy novelette)\n*1997 - Co-Winner, Bram Stoker Award, Year's Best Horror Novel (with Janet Berliner)\n*2007 - Finalist, Benjamin Franklin Award, Year's Best Book about Education, The Kids from Nowhere\n*2013 - First Place, Las Vegas International Film Festival, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n*2013 - First Place, Moondance International Film Festival, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n*2013 - First Place, Silent River International Film Festival, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n*2013 - First Place, New Hampshire International Film Festival, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n*2013 - Finalist, Portland International Film Festival, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n*2013 - Second Place, Kay Snow Writing Competition, The Kids from Nowhere (screenplay), with Deborah Schildt\n\n==Educational Awards and Achievements==\n*1984 Future Problem Solving National Coach of the Year\n*1988 First Alaskan to be awarded Christa McAuliffe Fellowship\n*1990 Named (Simon & Schuster, Inc.) as one of America's top 78 teachers\n*1993 Profiled (Delacorte Press) as one of world's top educators\n*1996 Fulbright Scholar: Trained professors in the Caribbean \n*2001 Co-recipient, Alaska's first Distance Educator of the Year Award\n*2010 University of Alaska Fairbanks Exemplary Service Award\n*2013 University of Alaska Fairbanks Outstanding Faculty Advisor Award\n*2015 Professor Emeritus, University of Alaska Fairbanks\n*2018 Teaching Recognition Award, University of Maryland University College\n*2019 Finalist, Stanley J. Drazek Award for Teaching Excellence, University of Maryland University College\n\nGuthridge also helped develop the Rural Alaska Honors Institute (RAHI). It has become one of the nation's top college preparatory programs for Native Americans. Over 2000 of its graduates have gone on to college success, including at such institutions as Harvard, Dartmouth, Yale, Norte Dame, Stanford, Berkeley, West Point, Annapolis, and the Air Force Academy.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bram Stoker Award for Best Novel]]\n*[[Time Machine (book series)]]\n*[[Nebula Award for Best Short Story]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{isfdb name|id=George_Guthridge|name=George Guthridge}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Guthridge, George}}\n[[Category:20th-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American novelists]]\n[[Category:American educators]]\n[[Category:American fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:American horror writers]]\n[[Category:American male novelists]]\n[[Category:American science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Portland State University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Alaska Fairbanks alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Montana alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Guthridge"}
{"title_page": "Jim Bolger", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image = Jim Bolger 2018 (cropped).jpg\n|caption = Bolger in 2018\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = Jim Bolger\n|honorific-suffix = [[Order of New Zealand|ONZ]]\n|order = [[List of Prime Ministers of New Zealand|35th Prime Minister of New Zealand]]\n|term_start = 2 November 1990\n|term_end = 8 December 1997\n|monarch = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|1blankname = {{nowrap|Governor-General}}\n|1namedata = [[Paul Reeves]]<br />[[Catherine Tizard]]<br />[[Michael Hardie Boys]]\n|predecessor = [[Mike Moore (New Zealand politician)|Mike Moore]]\n|successor = [[Jenny Shipley]]\n|deputy = [[Don McKinnon]] (1990\u201396)<br />[[Winston Peters]] (1996\u201397)\n|order2 = 25th [[Leader of the Opposition (New Zealand)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n|term_start2 = 26 March 1986\n|term_end2 = 2 November 1990\n|predecessor2 = [[Jim McLay]]\n|successor2 = [[Mike Moore (New Zealand politician)|Mike Moore]]\n|deputy2 = [[George Gair]]\n|constituency_MP4 = [[King Country (New Zealand electorate)|King Country]]<br />{{small|[[Taranaki-King Country]] (1996\u20131998)}}\n|parliament4  = New Zealand\n|term_start4  = 1972\n|term_end4    = 1998\n|predecessor4 = \n|successor4   = [[Shane Ardern]]\n|birth_name = James Brendan Bolger\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1935|5|31|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Opunake]], [[Taranaki]], New Zealand\n|spouse = {{marriage|Joan Maureen Riddell|1963}}\n|children = 9\n|parents = Daniel Bolger<br />Cecilia Doyle\n|party = [[New Zealand National Party|National]]\n|profession = Politician, businessman\n}}\n{{Jim Bolger sidebar}}\n\n'''James Brendan Bolger''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|size=100%|ONZ|PC}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u028c|l|d\u0292|\u0259r}} {{respell|BUL|j\u0259r}}; born 31 May 1935) is a [[List of New Zealand politicians|New Zealand politician]] of the [[New Zealand National Party|National Party]] who was the [[List of Prime Ministers of New Zealand|35th Prime Minister of New Zealand]], serving from 1990 to 1997.\n\nBolger was born to an [[Irish diaspora|Irish immigrant]] family in [[Opunake]], [[Taranaki]]. Before entering politics, he farmed in the [[Waikato]] and was involved in [[Federated Farmers]], a nationwide agricultural association. Bolger won election to Parliament in [[1972 New Zealand general election|1972]], and subsequently served in several portfolios in the [[Third National Government of New Zealand|Third National Government]]. Following one unsuccessful bid for the party leadership in [[1984 New Zealand National Party leadership election|1984]], Bolger was elected as [[Leader of the New Zealand National Party|National Party leader]] in [[1986 New Zealand National Party leadership election|1986]].  He served as [[Leader of the Opposition (New Zealand)|Leader of the Opposition]] from 1986 to 1990.\n\nBolger led the National Party to a [[landslide victory]]\u2014the largest in its history\u2014in the {{NZ election link|1990}}, allowing him to become Prime Minister on 2 November 1990. The [[Fourth National Government of New Zealand|Fourth National Government]] was elected on the promise of delivering a \"Decent Society\" following the [[Fourth Labour Government of New Zealand|previous Labour government]]'s economic reforms, known as \"[[Rogernomics]]\", which Bolger criticised. However, shortly after taking office, his government was forced to bail out the [[Bank of New Zealand]] and as a result reneged on a number of promises made during the election campaign. Bolger's government essentially advanced the [[Free market|free-market]] reforms of the previous government, while implementing drastic cuts in public spending. National retained power in the [[1993 New Zealand general election|1993 election]], albeit with a much-reduced majority.\n\nBolger's second term in office saw the introduction of the [[Electoral reform in New Zealand|MMP electoral system]]. In the subsequent [[1996 New Zealand general election|1996 election]] National emerged as the largest party but it was forced to enter into a coalition with [[New Zealand First]]. Bolger continued as Prime Minister, however his critics argued that he gave the inexperienced NZ First too much influence in his Cabinet. On 8 December 1997, Bolger was effectively [[1997 New Zealand National Party leadership election|ousted as leader]] by his party caucus, and was replaced as Prime Minister by [[Jenny Shipley]].\n\nAfter resigning as a Member of Parliament in 1998, Bolger became [[List of ambassadors of New Zealand to the United States|Ambassador to the United States]] and remained in this post until 2002.\n\n==Early life==\nBolger was born in 1935 in [[Opunake]] in Taranaki. He was born into an [[Irish Catholic]] family; Bolger was one of five children<ref name=\"wolfe\">{{citation|title=Battlers Bluffers & Bully Boys|author=Richard Wolfe|publisher=Random House New Zealand|isbn=978-1-86941-715-4|year=2005}}</ref> born to Daniel and Cecilia (n\u00e9e Doyle) Bolger<ref name=\"bassett\">{{cite web|url=http://www.enniscorthyguardian.ie/news/craanford-native-cecilia-104-passes-away-in-new-zealand-619754.html|title=Craanford native, Cecilia (104) passes away in New Zealand|author=[[Enniscorthy Guardian]]|date=April 2006}}</ref> who emigrated together from [[Gorey]], [[County Wexford]], in 1930. He left [[Opunake High School]] at age 15 to work on the family [[dairy farm]].<ref name=\"bassett1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.michaelbassett.co.nz/article_bolger.htm|title=Jim Bolger biography|author=[[Michael Bassett]]|date=December 1997|accessdate=27 July 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309204535/http://www.michaelbassett.co.nz/article_bolger.htm|archivedate=9 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1963 he married Joan Riddell, and they moved to their own sheep and beef farm in [[Te Kuiti]] two years later.<ref name=\"wolfe\"/> During this time Bolger became involved in local farmer politics. In the late 1960s he was asked to accompany the then [[Minister of Finance (New Zealand)|Minister of Finance]] [[Robert Muldoon]] to see for himself the difficulties faced by farmers in the area. As Bolger travelled around the district, he became experienced with Muldoon's adversarial style.<ref name=\"wolfe\"/>\n\n==Political career==\n===Member of Parliament===\n{{NZ parlbox header|align=left}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=37th|start={{NZ election link year|1972}}|end=1975|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=[[King Country (New Zealand electorate)|King Country]]}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=38th|start={{NZ election link year|1975}}|end=1978|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=39th|start={{NZ election link year|1978}}|end=1981|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=40th|start={{NZ election link year|1981}}|end=1984|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=41st|start={{NZ election link year|1984}}|end=1987|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=42nd|start={{NZ election link year|1987}}|end=1990|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=43rd|start={{NZ election link year|1990}}|end=1993|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=44th|start={{NZ election link year|1993}}|end=1996|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=45th|start={{NZ election link year|1996}}|end=1998|party=New Zealand National Party|\nelectorate=[[Taranaki-King Country]]\n|list=1}}\n{{NZ parlbox footer}}\n\nBolger entered politics in [[1972 New Zealand general election|1972]] as the [[New Zealand National Party]] Member of [[New Zealand Parliament|Parliament]] for [[King Country (New Zealand electorate)|King Country]], a newly created electorate in the rural western portion of North Island. This electorate is traditional National territory, and Bolger won easily. He represented this electorate, renamed [[Taranaki-King Country]] in 1996, until his retirement in 1998. In 1977 he was made a cabinet minister under Prime Minister [[Robert Muldoon]], first as New Zealand's [[Minister of Fisheries (New Zealand)|Minister of Fisheries]] and Associate Minister of Agriculture (1977), later as [[Minister of Labour (New Zealand)|Minister of Labour]] and [[Minister of Immigration (New Zealand)|Minister of Immigration]] following the 1978 election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://executive.govt.nz/93-96/minister/pm/INDEX.HTML|title=Rt Hon Jim Bolger|publisher=New Zealand Government|accessdate=6 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407171926/http://www.beehive.govt.nz/|archive-date=7 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter the defeat of National at the [[1984 New Zealand general election|1984 general elections]], Bolger and deputy leader [[Jim McLay]] challenged Muldoon for the leadership of the party. McLay succeeded and named Bolger as deputy leader (and hence [[Deputy Leader of the Opposition (New Zealand)|Deputy Leader of the Opposition]]). However, in 1986 Bolger successfully challenged McLay's leadership. Initially Bolger pursued a pro law and order approach, with a focus on critiquing Labour's perceived reluctance to combat \"lawlessness\" and offering a referendum on the reintroduction of [[capital punishment]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pratt|first1=John|last2=Treacher|first2=Phillip|date=December 1988|title=Law and Order and the 1987 New Zealand Election|journal=Aust & NZ Journal of Criminology|volume=21|issue=4|pages=253\u2013254|doi=10.1177/000486588802100407}}</ref> Following an unsuccessful election in [[1987 New Zealand general election|1987]], National under Bolger capitalised on public anger at the Labour government's highly unpopular economic policies to win National's biggest ever majority (and by extension the largest in New Zealand history) at the [[1990 New Zealand general election|1990]]. As a result, Bolger became Prime Minister at the age of 55.<ref name=\"nzhistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/people/jim-bolger|date=22 August 2014|publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]]|title=NZ History online: Biographies \u2013 Jim Bolger|accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Prime Minister===\n{{main|Fourth National Government of New Zealand}}\n{{Expand section|date=May 2018}}\n[[File:Bolger, 1992.jpg|thumb|upright|Bolger in 1992]]\n\n====First term====\nThree days after being sworn in as Prime Minister, Bolger's government needed to bail out the [[Bank of New Zealand]], then the largest bank in the country. The cost of the bail out was $380&nbsp;million, but after rewriting its budget, the government needed to borrow $740&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE6D81431F935A35752C1A966958260|title=New Zealand Bank Bailout|author=[[Reuters]]|date=6 November 1990|work=New York Times|accessdate=22 December 2008}}</ref> This had an immediate impact on Bolger's direction in government, with the first budget of his premiership being dubbed the \"Mother of All Budgets\".<ref name=\"past_budgets\">{{cite web|url=http://www.guide2.co.nz/politics/news/a-summary-of-some-major-budgets-from-the-past/11/8091|title=A Summary Of Some Major Budgets From The Past|date=24 May 2009|publisher=[[NZPA]]}}</ref> Bolger's [[Minister of Finance (New Zealand)|Finance Minister]], [[Ruth Richardson]], implemented drastic cuts in public spending, particularly in health and welfare. The [[Unemployment benefits|unemployment benefit]] was cut by $14.00 a week, sickness benefit by $27.04, families benefit by $25.00 to $27.00 and universal payments for family benefits were completely abolished.<ref name=\"Revolution\">{{cite web |last1=Russell|first1=Marcia|last2=Carlaw|first2=John|title=Revolution (part four) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MsvmVKqkX_o |website=YouTube|accessdate=4 February 2017|ref=Revpt4|location=14:44-15:18|format=video|date=1996}}</ref> Richardson also introduced many [[user pays]] requirements in hospitals and schools, services previously free to the populace and paid for by the government.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10418702|title=New Zealand as it might have been: From Ruthanasia to President Bolger| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=12 January 2007|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref> The first budget specifically reversed National's election promise to remove the tax surcharge on [[Pension|superannuation]] and the retention of promises to abolish tertiary fees.<ref name=\"past_budgets\"/>\n\nAnother major controversial piece of legislation was the 1991 [[Employment Contracts Act]] which effectively dismantled the industrial relations settlement that had remained in place since 1894, abolishing nation-wide industry awards. The immediate effects were felt with union membership falling dramatically in the immediate years following its adoption.<ref>[https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=mpbWpFrgc6sC&pg=RA6-PA24&lpg=RA6-PA24&dq=mike+moore+rogernomics&source=bl&ots=vKKOABXGx8&sig=ACfU3U2N_kw0idokp2n3AcNSRPWbXfH3Ng&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiMssuG5e7mAhUwzTgGHU-XAF4Q6AEwEHoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=mike%20moore%20rogernomics&f=false Foreign Labor Trends] United States Department of Labor, Bureau of Labor Affairs, American Embassy Motevideo</ref> His government also introduced the Building Act 1991, which is seen by some as the most crucial factor leading to the [[leaky homes crisis]] in the decade following its introduction.<ref name=\"RUD\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/auckland-region/news/article.cfm?l_id=117&objectid=10598019 |title=Brian Rudman: Government must plug those leaks|author=Rudman, Brian|authorlink=Brian Rudman|date=18 September 2009|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate=6 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nBolger opposed electoral reform,<ref name=\"nzhistory\"/> but despite his party's opposition held a referendum on whether or not New Zealand should change from the British-style electoral system of 'first past the post' to one of [[proportional representation]]. In 1992, New Zealanders voted to change to the [[Mixed-member proportional representation|Mixed Member Proportional]] (MMP) system. This was confirmed in a binding referendum held at the same time as the 1993 general election, which National won. Bolger had originally proposed a return to a [[bicameral]] system, with a [[Parliament of New Zealand#Senate proposals|Senate]] elected by [[Single Transferable Vote]],<ref name=\"nzhistory\"/> but this proposal was dropped in the face of support for electoral reform.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n====Second term====\n\nAt the [[1993 New Zealand general election|1993 election]], National was narrowly able to retain government owing partly to a slight economic recovery and the opposition being split between three competing parties; Bolger himself expected a comfortable election win, exclaiming \"bugger the pollsters\" upon the election result. National's unprecedented eighteen-seat majority had virtually disappeared and the country faced an election night [[hung parliament]] for the first time since [[New Zealand general election, 1931|1931]], with National one seat short of the required 50 seats to govern. Final [[special vote]]s counted over the following days revealed National had won {{NZ electorate link|Waitaki}}, allowing it to form a government with the majority of one seat but required the election of a Speaker from the opposition benches ([[Peter Tapsell (New Zealand politician)|Peter Tapsell]] of the Labour Party) to hold a working majority in the House.\n\nFollowing this election result Bolger expressed the need to work with other political parties and decided to demote Richardson from her post, appointing [[Bill Birch]] who was seen as more moderate. During Birch's tenure, spending on core areas such as health<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moh.govt.nz/moh.nsf/82f4780aa066f8d7cc2570bb006b5d4d/8399fc0f59415f4bcc256c7e007165be/$FILE/expenditure.pdf |title=Health Expenditure Trends in New Zealand 1990\u20132001 |year=2001 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and education increased. His government passed the [[Fiscal Responsibility Act 1994]]. During the 1994 Address-in-Reply debate, Bolger argued in favour of a [[Republicanism in New Zealand|New Zealand republic]], Bolger denied that his views related to his Irish heritage.<ref name=\"bolger_bio\">{{cite book|title=Bolger: A view from the top \u2013 my seven years as Prime Minister|author=Jim Bolger|publisher=Viking|year=1998|isbn=978-0-670-88369-1}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1995 the [[Cave Creek disaster]] gained public attention after a scenic viewing platform collapsed, killing fourteen people. The platform had been erected by the [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] in 1994 and later inquiries found that many of those who constructed it did not have prerequisite qualifications for building the platform. Despite DOC taking responsibility for its collapse, there would be no prosecutions (as the Crown is unable to prosecute itself) but $2.6 million worth of compensation was paid to the victims' families. Bolger initially attacked the report produced by the Commission of Inquiry, arguing that the platform failed \"essentially because it lacked about $20 worth of bolts to hold it together\". The Minister of Conservation, [[Denis Marshall]], was criticised in the media for his management of the Department. Many people blamed Marshall, although there was also wide criticism of the whole government's policies on management of the conservation estate. Marshall eventually resigned in May 1996, just over a year after the accident occurred. A new Minister, [[Nick Smith (New Zealand politician)|Nick Smith]], was appointed, and a full review of the Department was conducted by the State Services Commission.\n\nProposals to end the status of the [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]] as the country's highest court of appeal failed to gain parliamentary sanction during Bolger's premiership (however Helen Clark's [[Fifth Labour Government of New Zealand|Fifth Labour Government]] would replace the right of appeal in 2003 when it set up the [[Supreme Court of New Zealand]]). Bolger's government ended the awarding of [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the United Kingdom|British honours]] in 1996, introducing a [[New Zealand Honours System]]. At a conference on the \"Bolger years\" in 2007, Bolger recalled speaking to the Queen about the issue of New Zealand becoming a republic: \"I have more than once spoken with Her Majesty about my view that New Zealand would at some point elect its own Head of State, we discussed the matter in a most sensible way and she was in no way surprised or alarmed and neither did she cut my head off.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1/story.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10436441|title=Bolger told Queen monarchy's time numbered|author=Maggie Tait|accessdate=27 April 2007|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=27 April 2007}}</ref> With the new MMP environment some National Party MPs defected to a new grouping, [[United New Zealand]] in mid-1995, whilst other splinter parties emerged.\n\n====Third term====\nThe 1996 election saw the New Zealand First Party, led by [[Winston Peters]], holding the balance of power after the [[1996 New Zealand general election|1996 election]]. Bolger's government stayed in office in a caretaker role while negotiations began for a coalition government. Although National remained the largest single party, neither Bolger nor Labour leader [[Helen Clark]] could form a government on their own.  The balance of power in the new House rested with [[New Zealand First]], a party that had only been formed three years earlier. Its leader, [[Winston Peters]], had left the National Party to form his own party, opposing many of the free-market policies implemented by National and Labour before it.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} Ultimately, in December 1996, Peters decided to go into coalition with National.  Bolger had to pay a very high price in order to stay in power, however.  As part of a detailed coalition agreement Peters became Deputy Prime Minister and Treasurer (senior to the existing post of Finance Minister - which was retained by Birch). Although Bolger had previously sacked Peters from a National cabinet the two initially seemed to work well together.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n====Resignation====\n[[File:Jenny Shipley.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Jenny Shipley]] mounted a coup against Bolger in December 1997]]\nGrowing opposition to Bolger's slow pace and perceived exaggerated influence of New Zealand First led Transport Minister [[Jenny Shipley]] to stage a caucus room coup in 1997. Bolger was out of the country at the time, and when he returned he found that he did not have enough support in his caucus to remain as party leader and prime minister. Rather than face being voted out, he resigned on 8 December, and Shipley became New Zealand's first woman prime minister. As a concession, Bolger was made a junior minister in Shipley's government.<ref name=\"usnzcouncil\">{{cite web|title=Rt Hon. James Bolger Bio|url=http://usnzcouncil.org/rt-hon-james-bolger-bio/|publisher=New Zealand Council|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nBolger remains National's second-longest-serving leader. Retiring politician journalist [[Peter Luke]] said that Bolger was \"[t]he most under-estimated prime minister I have come across. He made up for his lack of education by having an innate ability to relate to the aspirations of ordinary Kiwis. And, as many civil servants discovered to their cost, his image of being a simple King Country farmer did not mean that he would not understand their reports and unfailingly point to the flaws in them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/opinion/5599333/Finding-truth-in-shades-of-grey |title= Finding truth in shades of grey|publisher= [[The Press]]|date= 14 September 2011|accessdate= 14 September 2011|author= [[Peter Luke]]}}</ref>\n\n==Life after politics==\n[[File:Jim Bolger.jpg|thumb|Bolger presides over a student's graduation at the [[University of Waikato]], 2008]]\nBolger retired as MP for Taranaki-King Country in 1998, prompting the {{By-election link|Taranaki-King Country|1998}} and subsequently became [[List of ambassadors of New Zealand to the United States|New Zealand's Ambassador to the United States]].<ref name=\"usnzcouncil\"/> On his return to New Zealand in 2001, he was appointed{{by whom|date=December 2016}} Chairman of the state-owned [[New Zealand Post]] and of its subsidiary [[Kiwibank]]. He also chairs Express Couriers Ltd, Trustees Executors Ltd, the Gas Industry Company Ltd, the Advisory Board of the World Agricultural Forum, St. Louis, USA, the New Zealand United States Council, and the Board of Directors of the Ian Axford Fellowships in Public Policy.<ref name=\"usnzcouncil\"/>\n\nBolger was elected Chancellor of the [[University of Waikato]] on 14 February 2007, succeeding John Jackman.<ref>{{cite web|title=The University of Waikato Annual Report 2007|url=https://www.waikato.ac.nz/annualreport/2007/annualreport.pdf|publisher=[[University of Waikato]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2008, almost 15 years after his National government sold [[Tranz Rail|New Zealand Rail]] Ltd, the Labour-led government repurchased its successor [[Toll NZ]] Ltd (less its Tranz Link trucking and distribution arm), having repurchased the track network in 2004. Bolger became chair of the company, renamed [[KiwiRail]], a position he held until 1 July 2010. A number of commentators,<ref name=\"kiwirail\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kiwirail.co.nz/about-us/history-of-kiwirail/150yearsofrail/stories/kiwirail-begins.html|title=KiwiRail begins \u2013 Government purchase of rail business closed one rail history chapter and opened another|publisher=[[KiwiRail]]|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> including [[Winston Peters]], view this as ironic. In response, Bolger acknowledged his involvement in privatising New Zealand Rail, remarking that \"my life is full of ironies,\"<ref name=\"NZ_Herald_10519449\">{{cite news|url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1/story.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10519449|title= Govt: We paid top dollar for rail|author= Young, Audrey|date= 2 July 2008|work= [[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate= 6 October 2011}}</ref> and added that \"the world has changed.\"<ref name=\"kiwirail\" />\n\nOn 5 June 2018 Bolger was announced as the head of a government working group, tasked with reporting back on the design of Fair Pay Agreements by the end of the year.<ref name=\"Workplace shake up\">{{cite news |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/104466802/workplace-shake-up-in-governments-sights--jim-bolger-to-lead-pay-working-group |title=Workplace shake up in Government's sights \u2013 Jim Bolger to lead pay working group |author1=Watkins, Tracey |author2=Kirk, Stacey |date=5 June 2018 |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|accessdate=5 June 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\nIn 1977, Bolger was awarded the [[Queen Elizabeth II Silver Jubilee Medal]].<ref name=\"HBTQ\">{{cite book |last1=Taylor |first1=Alister |last2=Coddington |first2=Deborah |authorlink1=Alister Taylor |authorlink2=Deborah Coddington |title=Honoured by the Queen \u2013 New Zealand |year=1994 |publisher=New Zealand Who's Who Aotearoa |location=Auckland |isbn=0-908578-34-2 |page=71}}</ref> Both Jim and Joan Bolger received the [[New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal]], and, in 1993, the [[New Zealand Suffrage Centennial Medal]].<ref name=\"HBTQ\"/> In the [[1998 New Year Honours (New Zealand)|1998 New Year Honours]], Jim Bolger was appointed a [[Member of the Order of New Zealand]], and Joan Bolger was appointed a [[Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]] for services to the community.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Year honours list 1998 |url=https://dpmc.govt.nz/publications/new-year-honours-list-1998 |date=31 December 1997 |publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBolger and his wife Joan are [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholics]]. The couple has nine children. Bolger voted [[anti-abortion]] whenever the issue came up in a parliamentary [[conscience vote]].<ref>{{cite book|author=[[Marilyn Pryor]]|title=The Right to Live: The Abortion Battle of New Zealand|location=Auckland|publisher=Haelan Books|date=1985|ISBN=0-908630-23-9}}</ref> He is a member of [[Collegium International]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collegium-international.csregistry.org/tiki-index.php?page=Members&bl=y|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922180311/http://collegium-international.csregistry.org/tiki-index.php?page=Members&bl=y|url-status=dead|archive-date=22 September 2008|title=Members|publisher=Collegium International|accessdate=17 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nSome have made reference to Jim Bolger, ironically or affectionately, as the \"Great Helmsman\".<ref>\n{{cite book| chapter = 4: The changing party system| editor1-last = Boston| editor1-first = Jonathan| editor1-link = Jonathan Boston| editor2-last          = Levine| editor2-first = Stephen| editor3-last = McLeay| editor3-first = Elizabeth| editor4-last = Roberts| editor4-first = Nigel S.| title                 = New Zealand Under MMP: A New Politics?| chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7NVT7ZaSloC| location = Auckland| publisher             = Auckland University Press| date = 1996| page = 56| isbn  = 9781869401382| accessdate  = 2016-12-28| quote  = Just as Norway's Prime minister is a popular and respected figure, widely seen as a fit leader for her country, so can Jim Bolger lay claim to a similar role. The Prime Minister has relished the challenge of the transition to PR in New Zealand, basking in his role as the 'Great Helmsman'.\n}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite book | last1 = Harper | first1 = D. L. | last2 = Malcolm| first2 = Gerard| title = Surviving the Change: How Firms Adjusted to the New Environment| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9XKPAAAAIAAJ| series = Research monograph| volume = 56 | publisher = New Zealand Institute of Economic Research| date = 1991| page = 316 | accessdate = 2016-12-28 | quote = The key [...] was a steady hand on the tiller with 'the great helmsman' Jim Bolger [...].}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Electoral history of Jim Bolger]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070314003628/http://www.primeminister.govt.nz/oldpms/1990bolger.html Prime Minister\u2019s Office Biography] (archived)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-gov}}\n{{S-bef | before = [[Mike Moore (New Zealand politician)|Mike Moore]] }}\n{{S-ttl | title = [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] | years=1990\u20131997}}\n{{S-aft | after = [[Jenny Shipley]] }}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Jim McLay]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Leader of the Opposition (New Zealand)|Leader of the Opposition]] |years=1986\u20131990}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Mike Moore (New Zealand politician)|Mike Moore]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Peter Gordon (politician)|Peter Gordon]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Minister of Labour (New Zealand)|Minister of Labour]] |years=1978\u20131984}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Stan Rodger]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Frank Gill (politician)|Frank Gill]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Minister of Immigration (New Zealand)|Minister of Immigration]] |years=1978\u20131981}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Aussie Malcolm]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|new}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Minister of Fisheries (New Zealand)|Minister of Fisheries]] |years=1977\u20131978}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Duncan MacIntyre (New Zealand politician)|Duncan MacIntyre]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par | nz}}\n{{s-new | Constituency|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[King Country (New Zealand electorate)|Member of Parliament for King Country]] | years=1972\u20131996}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Taranaki-King Country (New Zealand electorate)|Member of Parliament for Taranaki-King Country]] | years=1996\u20131998}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Shane Ardern]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Jim McLay]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[New Zealand National Party|Leader of the National Party]]|years=1986\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Jenny Shipley]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title=[[New Zealand National Party|Deputy Leader of the National Party]]|years=1984\u20131986}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[George Gair]]}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Wood (diplomat)|John Wood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Ambassadors from New Zealand to the United States|Ambassador to the United States]]|years=1998\u20132002}}\n{{s-aft|after=John Wood}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{New Zealand prime ministers}}\n{{NZ National Party}}\n{{Order of New Zealand}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bolger, Jim}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of New Zealand to the United States]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition (New Zealand)]]\n[[Category:New Zealand farmers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand MPs for North Island electorates]]\n[[Category:New Zealand National Party MPs]]\n[[Category:New Zealand National Party leaders]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand republicans]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:People from Opunake]]\n[[Category:People from Te Kuiti]]\n[[Category:People educated at Opunake High School]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the University of Waikato]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Zealand House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:New Zealand members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the New Zealand Suffrage Centennial Medal 1993]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Use New Zealand English|date=February 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image = Jim Bolger 2018 (cropped).jpg\n|caption = Bolger in 2018\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = Jim Bolger\n|honorific-suffix = [[Order of New Zealand|ONZ]]\n|order = [[List of Prime Ministers of New Zealand|35th Prime Minister of New Zealand]]\n|term_start = 2 November 1990\n|term_end = 8 December 1997\n|monarch = [[Elizabeth II]]\n|1blankname = {{nowrap|Governor-General}}\n|1namedata = [[Paul Reeves]]<br />[[Catherine Tizard]]<br />[[Michael Hardie Boys]]\n|predecessor = [[Mike Moore (New Zealand politician)|Mike Moore]]\n|successor = [[Jenny Shipley]]\n|deputy = [[Don McKinnon]] (1990\u201396)<br />[[Winston Peters]] (1996\u201397)\n|order2 = 25th [[Leader of the Opposition (New Zealand)|Leader of the Opposition]]\n|term_start2 = 26 March 1986\n|term_end2 = 2 November 1990\n|predecessor2 = [[Jim McLay]]\n|successor2 = [[Mike Moore (New Zealand politician)|Mike Moore]]\n|deputy2 = [[George Gair]]\n|constituency_MP4 = [[King Country (New Zealand electorate)|King Country]]<br />{{small|[[Taranaki-King Country]] (1996\u20131998)}}\n|parliament4  = New Zealand\n|term_start4  = 1972\n|term_end4    = 1998\n|predecessor4 = \n|successor4   = [[Shane Ardern]]\n|birth_name = James Brendan Bolger\n|birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1935|5|31|df=yes}}\n|birth_place = [[Opunake]], [[Taranaki]], New Zealand\n|spouse = {{marriage|Joan Maureen Riddell|1963}}\n|children = 9\n|parents = Daniel Bolger<br />Cecilia Doyle\n|party = [[New Zealand National Party|National]]\n|profession = Politician, businessman\n}}\n{{Jim Bolger sidebar}}\n\n'''James Brendan Bolger''' {{post-nominals|country=NZL|size=100%|ONZ|PC}} ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u028c|l|d\u0292|\u0259r}} {{respell|BUL|j\u0259r}}; born 31 May 1935) is a [[List of New Zealand politicians|New Zealand politician]] of the [[New Zealand National Party|National Party]] who was the [[List of Prime Ministers of New Zealand|35th Prime Minister of New Zealand]], serving from 1990 to 1997.\n\nBolger was born to an [[Irish diaspora|Irish immigrant]] family in [[Opunake]], [[Taranaki]]. Before entering politics, he farmed in the [[Waikato]] and was involved in [[Federated Farmers]], a nationwide agricultural association. Bolger won election to Parliament in [[1972 New Zealand general election|1972]], and subsequently served in several portfolios in the [[Third National Government of New Zealand|Third National Government]]. Following one unsuccessful bid for the party leadership in [[1984 New Zealand National Party leadership election|1984]], Bolger was elected as [[Leader of the New Zealand National Party|National Party leader]] in [[1986 New Zealand National Party leadership election|1986]].  He served as [[Leader of the Opposition (New Zealand)|Leader of the Opposition]] from 1986 to 1990.\n\nBolger led the National Party to a [[landslide victory]]\u2014the largest in its history\u2014in the {{NZ election link|1990}}, allowing him to become Prime Minister on 2 November 1990. The [[Fourth National Government of New Zealand|Fourth National Government]] was elected on the promise of delivering a \"Decent Society\" following the [[Fourth Labour Government of New Zealand|previous Labour government]]'s economic reforms, known as \"[[Rogernomics]]\", which Bolger criticised. However, shortly after taking office, his government was forced to bail out the [[Bank of New Zealand]] and as a result reneged on a number of promises made during the election campaign. Bolger's government essentially advanced the [[Free market|free-market]] reforms of the previous government, while implementing drastic cuts in public spending. National retained power in the [[1993 New Zealand general election|1993 election]], albeit with a much-reduced majority.\n\nBolger's second term in office saw the introduction of the [[Electoral reform in New Zealand|MMP electoral system]]. In the subsequent [[1996 New Zealand general election|1996 election]] National emerged as the largest party but it was forced to enter into a coalition with [[New Zealand First]]. Bolger continued as Prime Minister, however his critics argued that he gave the inexperienced NZ First too much influence in his Cabinet. On 8 December 1997, Bolger was effectively [[1997 New Zealand National Party leadership election|ousted as leader]] by his party caucus, and was replaced as Prime Minister by [[Jenny Shipley]].\n\nAfter resigning as a Member of Parliament in 1998, Bolger became [[List of ambassadors of New Zealand to the United States|Ambassador to the United States]] and remained in this post until 2002.\n\n==Early life==\nBolger was born in 1935 in [[Opunake]] in Taranaki. He was born into an [[Irish Catholic]] family; Bolger was one of five children<ref name=\"wolfe\">{{citation|title=Battlers Bluffers & Bully Boys|author=Richard Wolfe|publisher=Random House New Zealand|isbn=978-1-86941-715-4|year=2005}}</ref> born to Daniel and Cecilia (n\u00e9e Doyle) Bolger<ref name=\"bassett\">{{cite web|url=http://www.enniscorthyguardian.ie/news/craanford-native-cecilia-104-passes-away-in-new-zealand-619754.html|title=Craanford native, Cecilia (104) passes away in New Zealand|author=[[Enniscorthy Guardian]]|date=April 2006}}</ref> who emigrated together from [[Gorey]], [[County Wexford]], in 1930. He left [[Opunake High School]] at age 15 to work on the family [[dairy farm]].<ref name=\"bassett1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.michaelbassett.co.nz/article_bolger.htm|title=Jim Bolger biography|author=[[Michael Bassett]]|date=December 1997|accessdate=27 July 2007|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120309204535/http://www.michaelbassett.co.nz/article_bolger.htm|archivedate=9 March 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 1963 he married Joan Riddell, and they moved to their own sheep and beef farm in [[Te Kuiti]] two years later.<ref name=\"wolfe\"/> During this time Bolger became involved in local farmer politics. In the late 1960s he was asked to accompany the then [[Minister of Finance (New Zealand)|Minister of Finance]] [[Robert Muldoon]] to see for himself the difficulties faced by farmers in the area. As Bolger travelled around the district, he became experienced with Muldoon's adversarial style.<ref name=\"wolfe\"/>\n\n==Political career==\n===Member of Parliament===\n{{NZ parlbox header|align=left}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=37th|start={{NZ election link year|1972}}|end=1975|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=[[King Country (New Zealand electorate)|King Country]]}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=38th|start={{NZ election link year|1975}}|end=1978|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=39th|start={{NZ election link year|1978}}|end=1981|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=40th|start={{NZ election link year|1981}}|end=1984|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=41st|start={{NZ election link year|1984}}|end=1987|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=42nd|start={{NZ election link year|1987}}|end=1990|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=43rd|start={{NZ election link year|1990}}|end=1993|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=44th|start={{NZ election link year|1993}}|end=1996|party=New Zealand National Party\n|electorate=King Country\n}}\n{{NZ parlbox|term=45th|start={{NZ election link year|1996}}|end=1998|party=New Zealand National Party|\nelectorate=[[Taranaki-King Country]]\n|list=1}}\n{{NZ parlbox footer}}\n\nBolger entered politics in [[1972 New Zealand general election|1972]] as the [[New Zealand National Party]] Member of [[New Zealand Parliament|Parliament]] for [[King Country (New Zealand electorate)|King Country]], a newly created electorate in the rural western portion of North Island. This electorate is traditional National territory, and Bolger won easily. He represented this electorate, renamed [[Taranaki-King Country]] in 1996, until his retirement in 1998. In 1977 he was made a cabinet minister under Prime Minister [[Robert Muldoon]], first as New Zealand's [[Minister of Fisheries (New Zealand)|Minister of Fisheries]] and Associate Minister of Agriculture (1977), later as [[Minister of Labour (New Zealand)|Minister of Labour]] and [[Minister of Immigration (New Zealand)|Minister of Immigration]] following the 1978 election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://executive.govt.nz/93-96/minister/pm/INDEX.HTML|title=Rt Hon Jim Bolger|publisher=New Zealand Government|accessdate=6 October 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120407171926/http://www.beehive.govt.nz/|archive-date=7 April 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter the defeat of National at the [[1984 New Zealand general election|1984 general elections]], Bolger and deputy leader [[Jim McLay]] challenged Muldoon for the leadership of the party. McLay succeeded and named Bolger as deputy leader (and hence [[Deputy Leader of the Opposition (New Zealand)|Deputy Leader of the Opposition]]). However, in 1986 Bolger successfully challenged McLay's leadership. Initially Bolger pursued a pro law and order approach, with a focus on critiquing Labour's perceived reluctance to combat \"lawlessness\" and offering a referendum on the reintroduction of [[capital punishment]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Pratt|first1=John|last2=Treacher|first2=Phillip|date=December 1988|title=Law and Order and the 1987 New Zealand Election|journal=Aust & NZ Journal of Criminology|volume=21|issue=4|pages=253\u2013254|doi=10.1177/000486588802100407}}</ref> Following an unsuccessful election in [[1987 New Zealand general election|1987]], National under Bolger capitalised on public anger at the Labour government's highly unpopular economic policies to win National's biggest ever majority (and by extension the largest in New Zealand history) at the [[1990 New Zealand general election|1990]]. As a result, Bolger became Prime Minister at the age of 55.<ref name=\"nzhistory\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nzhistory.net.nz/people/jim-bolger|date=22 August 2014|publisher=[[Ministry for Culture and Heritage]]|title=NZ History online: Biographies \u2013 Jim Bolger|accessdate=21 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Prime Minister===\n{{main|Fourth National Government of New Zealand}}\n{{Expand section|date=May 2018}}\n[[File:Bolger, 1992.jpg|thumb|upright|Bolger in 1992]]\n\n====First term====\nThree days after being sworn in as Prime Minister, Bolger's government needed to bail out the [[Bank of New Zealand]], then the largest bank in the country. The cost of the bail out was $380&nbsp;million, but after rewriting its budget, the government needed to borrow $740&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9C0CE6D81431F935A35752C1A966958260|title=New Zealand Bank Bailout|author=[[Reuters]]|date=6 November 1990|work=New York Times|accessdate=22 December 2008}}</ref> This had an immediate impact on Bolger's direction in government, with the first budget of his premiership being dubbed the \"Mother of All Budgets\".<ref name=\"past_budgets\">{{cite web|url=http://www.guide2.co.nz/politics/news/a-summary-of-some-major-budgets-from-the-past/11/8091|title=A Summary Of Some Major Budgets From The Past|date=24 May 2009|publisher=[[NZPA]]}}</ref> Bolger's [[Minister of Finance (New Zealand)|Finance Minister]], [[Ruth Richardson]], implemented drastic cuts in public spending, particularly in health and welfare. The [[Unemployment benefits|unemployment benefit]] was cut by $14.00 a week, sickness benefit by $27.04, families benefit by $25.00 to $27.00 and universal payments for family benefits were completely abolished.<ref name=\"Revolution\">{{cite web |last1=Russell|first1=Marcia|last2=Carlaw|first2=John|title=Revolution (part four) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MsvmVKqkX_o |website=YouTube|accessdate=4 February 2017|ref=Revpt4|location=14:44-15:18|format=video|date=1996}}</ref> Richardson also introduced many [[user pays]] requirements in hospitals and schools, services previously free to the populace and paid for by the government.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10418702|title=New Zealand as it might have been: From Ruthanasia to President Bolger| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|date=12 January 2007|accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref> The first budget specifically reversed National's election promise to remove the tax surcharge on [[Pension|superannuation]] and the retention of promises to abolish tertiary fees.<ref name=\"past_budgets\"/>\n\nAnother major controversial piece of legislation was the 1991 [[Employment Contracts Act]] which effectively dismantled the industrial relations settlement that had remained in place since 1894, abolishing nation-wide industry awards. The immediate effects were felt with union membership falling dramatically in the immediate years following its adoption.<ref>[https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=mpbWpFrgc6sC&pg=RA6-PA24&lpg=RA6-PA24&dq=mike+moore+rogernomics&source=bl&ots=vKKOABXGx8&sig=ACfU3U2N_kw0idokp2n3AcNSRPWbXfH3Ng&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiMssuG5e7mAhUwzTgGHU-XAF4Q6AEwEHoECAoQAQ#v=onepage&q=mike%20moore%20rogernomics&f=false Foreign Labor Trends] United States Department of Labor, Bureau of Labor Affairs, American Embassy Motevideo</ref> His government also introduced the Building Act 1991, which is seen by some as the most crucial factor leading to the [[leaky homes crisis]] in the decade following its introduction.<ref name=\"RUD\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/auckland-region/news/article.cfm?l_id=117&objectid=10598019 |title=Brian Rudman: Government must plug those leaks|author=Rudman, Brian|authorlink=Brian Rudman|date=18 September 2009|work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate=6 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nBolger opposed electoral reform,<ref name=\"nzhistory\"/> but despite his party's opposition held a referendum on whether or not New Zealand should change from the British-style electoral system of 'first past the post' to one of [[proportional representation]]. In 1992, New Zealanders voted to change to the [[Mixed-member proportional representation|Mixed Member Proportional]] (MMP) system. This was confirmed in a binding referendum held at the same time as the 1993 general election, which National won. Bolger had originally proposed a return to a [[bicameral]] system, with a [[Parliament of New Zealand#Senate proposals|Senate]] elected by [[Single Transferable Vote]],<ref name=\"nzhistory\"/> but this proposal was dropped in the face of support for electoral reform.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n====Second term====\n\nAt the [[1993 New Zealand general election|1993 election]], National was narrowly able to retain government owing partly to a slight economic recovery and the opposition being split between three competing parties; Bolger himself expected a comfortable election win, exclaiming \"bugger the pollsters\" upon the election result. National's unprecedented eighteen-seat majority had virtually disappeared and the country faced an election night [[hung parliament]] for the first time since [[New Zealand general election, 1931|1931]], with National one seat short of the required 50 seats to govern. Final [[special vote]]s counted over the following days revealed National had won {{NZ electorate link|Waitaki}}, allowing it to form a government with the majority of one seat but required the election of a Speaker from the opposition benches ([[Peter Tapsell (New Zealand politician)|Peter Tapsell]] of the Labour Party) to hold a working majority in the House.\n\nFollowing this election result Bolger expressed the need to work with other political parties and decided to demote Richardson from her post, appointing [[Bill Birch]] who was seen as more moderate. During Birch's tenure, spending on core areas such as health<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moh.govt.nz/moh.nsf/82f4780aa066f8d7cc2570bb006b5d4d/8399fc0f59415f4bcc256c7e007165be/$FILE/expenditure.pdf |title=Health Expenditure Trends in New Zealand 1990\u20132001 |year=2001 }}{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and education increased. His government passed the [[Fiscal Responsibility Act 1994]]. During the 1994 Address-in-Reply debate, Bolger argued in favour of a [[Republicanism in New Zealand|New Zealand republic]], Bolger denied that his views related to his Irish heritage.<ref name=\"bolger_bio\">{{cite book|title=Bolger: A view from the top \u2013 my seven years as Prime Minister|author=Jim Bolger|publisher=Viking|year=1998|isbn=978-0-670-88369-1}}</ref>\n\nIn April 1995 the [[Cave Creek disaster]] gained public attention after a scenic viewing platform collapsed, killing fourteen people. The platform had been erected by the [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|Department of Conservation]] in 1994 and later inquiries found that many of those who constructed it did not have prerequisite qualifications for building the platform. Despite DOC taking responsibility for its collapse, there would be no prosecutions (as the Crown is unable to prosecute itself) but $2.6 million dollars worth of compensation was paid to the victims' families. Bolger initially attacked the report produced by the Commission of Inquiry, arguing that the platform failed \"essentially because it lacked about $20 worth of bolts to hold it together\". The Minister of Conservation, [[Denis Marshall]], was criticised in the media for his management of the Department. Many people blamed Marshall, although there was also wide criticism of the whole government's policies on management of the conservation estate. Marshall eventually resigned in May 1996, just over a year after the accident occurred. A new Minister, [[Nick Smith (New Zealand politician)|Nick Smith]], was appointed, and a full review of the Department was conducted by the State Services Commission.\n\nProposals to end the status of the [[Judicial Committee of the Privy Council]] as the country's highest court of appeal failed to gain parliamentary sanction during Bolger's premiership (however Helen Clark's [[Fifth Labour Government of New Zealand|Fifth Labour Government]] would replace the right of appeal in 2003 when it set up the [[Supreme Court of New Zealand]]). Bolger's government ended the awarding of [[Orders, decorations, and medals of the United Kingdom|British honours]] in 1996, introducing a [[New Zealand Honours System]]. At a conference on the \"Bolger years\" in 2007, Bolger recalled speaking to the Queen about the issue of New Zealand becoming a republic: \"I have more than once spoken with Her Majesty about my view that New Zealand would at some point elect its own Head of State, we discussed the matter in a most sensible way and she was in no way surprised or alarmed and neither did she cut my head off.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1/story.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10436441|title=Bolger told Queen monarchy's time numbered|author=Maggie Tait|accessdate=27 April 2007|work=The New Zealand Herald|date=27 April 2007}}</ref> With the new MMP environment some National Party MPs defected to a new grouping, [[United New Zealand]] in mid-1995, whilst other splinter parties emerged.\n\n====Third term====\nThe 1996 election saw the New Zealand First Party, led by [[Winston Peters]], holding the balance of power after the [[1996 New Zealand general election|1996 election]]. Bolger's government stayed in office in a caretaker role while negotiations began for a coalition government. Although National remained the largest single party, neither Bolger nor Labour leader [[Helen Clark]] could form a government on their own.  The balance of power in the new House rested with [[New Zealand First]], a party that had only been formed three years earlier. Its leader, [[Winston Peters]], had left the National Party to form his own party, opposing many of the free-market policies implemented by National and Labour before it.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}} Ultimately, in December 1996, Peters decided to go into coalition with National.  Bolger had to pay a very high price in order to stay in power, however.  As part of a detailed coalition agreement Peters became Deputy Prime Minister and Treasurer (senior to the existing post of Finance Minister - which was retained by Birch). Although Bolger had previously sacked Peters from a National cabinet the two initially seemed to work well together.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\n====Resignation====\n[[File:Jenny Shipley.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Jenny Shipley]] mounted a coup against Bolger in December 1997]]\nGrowing opposition to Bolger's slow pace and perceived exaggerated influence of New Zealand First led Transport Minister [[Jenny Shipley]] to stage a caucus room coup in 1997. Bolger was out of the country at the time, and when he returned he found that he did not have enough support in his caucus to remain as party leader and prime minister. Rather than face being voted out, he resigned on 8 December, and Shipley became New Zealand's first woman prime minister. As a concession, Bolger was made a junior minister in Shipley's government.<ref name=\"usnzcouncil\">{{cite web|title=Rt Hon. James Bolger Bio|url=http://usnzcouncil.org/rt-hon-james-bolger-bio/|publisher=New Zealand Council|accessdate=14 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nBolger remains National's second-longest-serving leader. Retiring politician journalist [[Peter Luke]] said that Bolger was \"[t]he most under-estimated prime minister I have come across. He made up for his lack of education by having an innate ability to relate to the aspirations of ordinary Kiwis. And, as many civil servants discovered to their cost, his image of being a simple King Country farmer did not mean that he would not understand their reports and unfailingly point to the flaws in them.\"<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/opinion/5599333/Finding-truth-in-shades-of-grey |title= Finding truth in shades of grey|publisher= [[The Press]]|date= 14 September 2011|accessdate= 14 September 2011|author= [[Peter Luke]]}}</ref>\n\n==Life after politics==\n[[File:Jim Bolger.jpg|thumb|Bolger presides over a student's graduation at the [[University of Waikato]], 2008]]\nBolger retired as MP for Taranaki-King Country in 1998, prompting the {{By-election link|Taranaki-King Country|1998}} and subsequently became [[List of ambassadors of New Zealand to the United States|New Zealand's Ambassador to the United States]].<ref name=\"usnzcouncil\"/> On his return to New Zealand in 2001, he was appointed{{by whom|date=December 2016}} Chairman of the state-owned [[New Zealand Post]] and of its subsidiary [[Kiwibank]]. He also chairs Express Couriers Ltd, Trustees Executors Ltd, the Gas Industry Company Ltd, the Advisory Board of the World Agricultural Forum, St. Louis, USA, the New Zealand United States Council, and the Board of Directors of the Ian Axford Fellowships in Public Policy.<ref name=\"usnzcouncil\"/>\n\nBolger was elected Chancellor of the [[University of Waikato]] on 14 February 2007, succeeding John Jackman.<ref>{{cite web|title=The University of Waikato Annual Report 2007|url=https://www.waikato.ac.nz/annualreport/2007/annualreport.pdf|publisher=[[University of Waikato]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 July 2008, almost 15 years after his National government sold [[Tranz Rail|New Zealand Rail]] Ltd, the Labour-led government repurchased its successor [[Toll NZ]] Ltd (less its Tranz Link trucking and distribution arm), having repurchased the track network in 2004. Bolger became chair of the company, renamed [[KiwiRail]], a position he held until 1 July 2010. A number of commentators,<ref name=\"kiwirail\">{{cite web|url=https://www.kiwirail.co.nz/about-us/history-of-kiwirail/150yearsofrail/stories/kiwirail-begins.html|title=KiwiRail begins \u2013 Government purchase of rail business closed one rail history chapter and opened another|publisher=[[KiwiRail]]|accessdate=8 May 2019}}</ref> including [[Winston Peters]], view this as ironic. In response, Bolger acknowledged his involvement in privatising New Zealand Rail, remarking that \"my life is full of ironies,\"<ref name=\"NZ_Herald_10519449\">{{cite news|url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/1/story.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10519449|title= Govt: We paid top dollar for rail|author= Young, Audrey|date= 2 July 2008|work= [[The New Zealand Herald]]|accessdate= 6 October 2011}}</ref> and added that \"the world has changed.\"<ref name=\"kiwirail\" />\n\nOn 5 June 2018 Bolger was announced as the head of a government working group, tasked with reporting back on the design of Fair Pay Agreements by the end of the year.<ref name=\"Workplace shake up\">{{cite news |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/politics/104466802/workplace-shake-up-in-governments-sights--jim-bolger-to-lead-pay-working-group |title=Workplace shake up in Government's sights \u2013 Jim Bolger to lead pay working group |author1=Watkins, Tracey |author2=Kirk, Stacey |date=5 June 2018 |work=[[Stuff.co.nz]]|accessdate=5 June 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\nIn 1977, Bolger was awarded the [[Queen Elizabeth II Silver Jubilee Medal]].<ref name=\"HBTQ\">{{cite book |last1=Taylor |first1=Alister |last2=Coddington |first2=Deborah |authorlink1=Alister Taylor |authorlink2=Deborah Coddington |title=Honoured by the Queen \u2013 New Zealand |year=1994 |publisher=New Zealand Who's Who Aotearoa |location=Auckland |isbn=0-908578-34-2 |page=71}}</ref> Both Jim and Joan Bolger received the [[New Zealand 1990 Commemoration Medal]], and, in 1993, the [[New Zealand Suffrage Centennial Medal]].<ref name=\"HBTQ\"/> In the [[1998 New Year Honours (New Zealand)|1998 New Year Honours]], Jim Bolger was appointed a [[Member of the Order of New Zealand]], and Joan Bolger was appointed a [[Companion of the New Zealand Order of Merit]] for services to the community.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Year honours list 1998 |url=https://dpmc.govt.nz/publications/new-year-honours-list-1998 |date=31 December 1997 |publisher=Department of the Prime Minister and Cabinet |accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBolger and his wife Joan are [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholics]]. The couple has nine children. Bolger voted [[anti-abortion]] whenever the issue came up in a parliamentary [[conscience vote]].<ref>{{cite book|author=[[Marilyn Pryor]]|title=The Right to Live: The Abortion Battle of New Zealand|location=Auckland|publisher=Haelan Books|date=1985|ISBN=0-908630-23-9}}</ref> He is a member of [[Collegium International]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collegium-international.csregistry.org/tiki-index.php?page=Members&bl=y|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922180311/http://collegium-international.csregistry.org/tiki-index.php?page=Members&bl=y|url-status=dead|archive-date=22 September 2008|title=Members|publisher=Collegium International|accessdate=17 May 2009}}</ref>\n\nSome have made reference to Jim Bolger, ironically or affectionately, as the \"Great Helmsman\".<ref>\n{{cite book| chapter = 4: The changing party system| editor1-last = Boston| editor1-first = Jonathan| editor1-link = Jonathan Boston| editor2-last          = Levine| editor2-first = Stephen| editor3-last = McLeay| editor3-first = Elizabeth| editor4-last = Roberts| editor4-first = Nigel S.| title                 = New Zealand Under MMP: A New Politics?| chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Y7NVT7ZaSloC| location = Auckland| publisher             = Auckland University Press| date = 1996| page = 56| isbn  = 9781869401382| accessdate  = 2016-12-28| quote  = Just as Norway's Prime minister is a popular and respected figure, widely seen as a fit leader for her country, so can Jim Bolger lay claim to a similar role. The Prime Minister has relished the challenge of the transition to PR in New Zealand, basking in his role as the 'Great Helmsman'.\n}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite book | last1 = Harper | first1 = D. L. | last2 = Malcolm| first2 = Gerard| title = Surviving the Change: How Firms Adjusted to the New Environment| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9XKPAAAAIAAJ| series = Research monograph| volume = 56 | publisher = New Zealand Institute of Economic Research| date = 1991| page = 316 | accessdate = 2016-12-28 | quote = The key [...] was a steady hand on the tiller with 'the great helmsman' Jim Bolger [...].}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Electoral history of Jim Bolger]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070314003628/http://www.primeminister.govt.nz/oldpms/1990bolger.html Prime Minister\u2019s Office Biography] (archived)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-gov}}\n{{S-bef | before = [[Mike Moore (New Zealand politician)|Mike Moore]] }}\n{{S-ttl | title = [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]] | years=1990\u20131997}}\n{{S-aft | after = [[Jenny Shipley]] }}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef | before = [[Jim McLay]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Leader of the Opposition (New Zealand)|Leader of the Opposition]] |years=1986\u20131990}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Mike Moore (New Zealand politician)|Mike Moore]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Peter Gordon (politician)|Peter Gordon]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Minister of Labour (New Zealand)|Minister of Labour]] |years=1978\u20131984}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Stan Rodger]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef | before = [[Frank Gill (politician)|Frank Gill]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Minister of Immigration (New Zealand)|Minister of Immigration]] |years=1978\u20131981}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Aussie Malcolm]]}}\n|-\n{{s-new|new}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Minister of Fisheries (New Zealand)|Minister of Fisheries]] |years=1977\u20131978}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Duncan MacIntyre (New Zealand politician)|Duncan MacIntyre]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par | nz}}\n{{s-new | Constituency|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[King Country (New Zealand electorate)|Member of Parliament for King Country]] | years=1972\u20131996}}\n{{s-non | reason = Constituency abolished }}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title = [[Taranaki-King Country (New Zealand electorate)|Member of Parliament for Taranaki-King Country]] | years=1996\u20131998}}\n{{s-aft | after = [[Shane Ardern]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Jim McLay]]|rows=2}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[New Zealand National Party|Leader of the National Party]]|years=1986\u20131997}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Jenny Shipley]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl | title=[[New Zealand National Party|Deputy Leader of the National Party]]|years=1984\u20131986}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[George Gair]]}}\n|-\n{{s-dip}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John Wood (diplomat)|John Wood]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Ambassadors from New Zealand to the United States|Ambassador to the United States]]|years=1998\u20132002}}\n{{s-aft|after=John Wood}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{New Zealand prime ministers}}\n{{NZ National Party}}\n{{Order of New Zealand}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bolger, Jim}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of New Zealand to the United States]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Opposition (New Zealand)]]\n[[Category:New Zealand farmers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand MPs for North Island electorates]]\n[[Category:New Zealand National Party MPs]]\n[[Category:New Zealand National Party leaders]]\n[[Category:New Zealand people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:New Zealand republicans]]\n[[Category:New Zealand Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:People from Opunake]]\n[[Category:People from Te Kuiti]]\n[[Category:People educated at Opunake High School]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the University of Waikato]]\n[[Category:Members of the New Zealand House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Members of 