{"title_page": "Android Team Awareness Kit", "text_new": "The '''Team Awareness Kit''' for '''Android''' / '''Tactical Assault Kit''' for '''Android''' ('''ATAK''') is an [[Android (operating system)|Android]] smartphone geospatial infrastructure and military situational awareness app. It allows for precision targeting, surrounding land formation intelligence, situational awareness, navigation, and data sharing. This Android app is a part of the larger TAK family of products.<ref>https://takmaps.com/about/</ref>  ATAK has a plugin architecture which allows developers to add functionality.\n\nInitially created in 2010 by the [[Air Force Research Laboratory]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wpafb.af.mil/shared/media/document/|title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-05-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140520234009/http://www.wpafb.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-131008-023.pdf |archivedate=2014-05-20 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.cs.drexel.edu/~kfu22/you/docs/FP-MILCOM-Paper.pdf]{{dead link|date=December 2019}}</ref> and based on the NASA WorldWind Mobile codebase its development and deployment grew slowly then rapidly since 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbo.gov/index?s=opportunity&mode=form&tab=core&id=8f69fc9a1ac486675a2d08a5ac57cc41|title=58--RFI for Mobile Communications Device SOF-NEXTGEN-RADIO - Federal Business Opportunities: Opportunities|website=www.fbo.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dhs.gov/science-and-technology/news/2017/11/17/snapshot-atak-increases-situational-awareness-communication|title=Snapshot: ATAK increases situational awareness, communication|date=November 17, 2017|website=Department of Homeland Security}}</ref>.  \n \nAs of 2019, ATAK has an estimated 175,000 military and civilian users across numerous public safety agencies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insights.samsung.com/2019/10/16/atak-improves-situational-awareness-for-california-fire-department/|title=ATAK Improves Situational Awareness for California Fire Department|date=2019-10-16|website=Samsung Business Insights|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref>\n\n\n==History and Connections to other programs==\n\nATAK began in August 2010 and was originally based on NASA's WorldWind Mobile.  The goal was to demonstrate robust information sharing in a mobile format.\n\nIn 2013, officials at Draper Laboratory said that the system would be compatible with [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[mobile operating system]]s and could be used for navigation, [[spatial awareness]], and controlling [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drones]].<ref>Denise Chow, [http://www.nbcnews.com/id/53336049/ns/technology_and_science-science/t/troops-call-military-airstrike-theres-app/ Troops Call for Military Airstrike? There's an App for That], ''LiveScience'' (October 21, 2013).</ref>\n\nIn Oct 14, 2014 U.S. [[Army Geospatial Center]] recommended [[AFRL]]'s [[Android Team Awareness Kit (ATAK)]], over the world-leader [[Commercial Joint Mapping Toolkit|Esri's Commercial Joint Mapping Tool Kit (CJMTK)]], [[NASA]]'s [[World Wind]], and the Army's Globe Engine (AGE) for map engine driving the Nett Warrior End User Device.  ATAK was selected due to similar capabilities with CJMTK, similar risk, and less than one-third of the total cost.  Read the full, public released report [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:US_Army%27s_Nett_Warrior_Map_Engine_Trade_Study_Report.pdf Nett Warrior Map Engine Trade Study].\n\nAccording to a January 2016 article in National Defense Magazine, \"[ATAK] has already been fielded to AFSOC units\".\n\nIn September 2015, DARPA reported that ATAK was used in a successful demonstration of the Persistent Close Air Support Program, and is in use by thousands of users.\n\nPolaris integrated its Ground Guidance software into an ATAK Plugin to allow on and off-road routing for mounted and dismounted soldiers, accounting for terrain, weather, enemy activity and equipment load.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://soldiersystems.net/2015/11/12/juggernaut-board-mff-t2/|title=Juggernaut.Board MFF-T2 - Soldier Systems Daily|website=soldiersystems.net|language=en-US|access-date=2018-07-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, [[USAF]] Security Forces deployed ATAK at Eglin AFB, Florida. <ref>https://www.eglin.af.mil/News/Article-Display/Article/1572874/defenders-go-mobile-with-new-comm-system/</ref>\n\nThe ATAK app has several versions.  In 2020, ATAK-PR (Android Tactical Assault Kit - Public Release) was made available for download on [https://takmaps.com/ takmaps.com]; it lacks military-only capabilities.\n\n==Other Versions==\n\nIn addition to the Android version, there is also a Windows version (WinTak) and an iPhone version under development (iTak).  WinTAK is an application developed for Microsoft Windows Operating System which uses maps to allow for precise targeting, intelligence on surrounding land formations, navigation, and generalized situational awareness. It was developed in conjunction with ATAK to provide similar functionality on a Windows platform.\n\n==Commercial Licensing==\n\nIn January 2015, AFRL began licensing ATAK through TechLink to U. S. companies, for commercial use to support state/local government uses as well as civilian uses.  As of January 2020, one hundred companies have licensed ATAK for commercial uses.<ref>{{cite web |title=ATAK |url=https://techlinkcenter.org/technologies/android-team-awareness-kit-atak/ |website=TechLink |publisher=TechLink |accessdate=29 January 2020}}</ref> Corona Fire Department is one example of a local public safety agency using ATAK. Corona uses PAR Government's Team Connect platform to leverage ATAK. In civilian use, ATAK is often referred to as Android Team Awareness Kit.\n==Direct Download from the Federal Government==\n\nAs of March 31, 2020, the civilian version of ATAK, referred to as CivTAK has been approved for \"Public Release by Army Night Vision and is available for download [http://7n7.us/2 here].\n\n[[File:ATAK Tech Transfer brief 2014 03 31.pdf|thumb|Android Team Awareness Kit (ATAK) Licensing for Tech Transfer & Tech Transition.  Briefing.  DISTRIBUTION STATEMENT A: Approved for Public Release,  Case Number 88ABW-2014-1324]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tojMXYMVdyw ATAK 3.6 Promo video]\n* [https://takmaps.com/ Official TAK website]\n*[https://TAKCiv.org TAKCiv.org] collects public information and news about the TAK program.\n*There is a Reddit site for ATAK ([https://Reddit.com/r/ATAK Reddit.com/r/ATAK]).\n*There is a [https://discord.gg/cYD2N3T Discord site] for discussion and development of  open source TAK related tools.\n* Do not use / trust atakmap.com.\n\n[[Category:Android (operating system)]]\n[[Category:Geographic information systems]]\n", "text_old": "The '''Team Awareness Kit''' for '''Android''' / '''Tactical Assault Kit''' for '''Android''' ('''ATAK''') is an [[Android (operating system)|Android]] smartphone geospatial infrastructure and military situational awareness app. It allows for precision targeting, surrounding land formation intelligence, situational awareness, navigation, and data sharing. This Android app is a part of the larger TAK family of products.<ref>https://takmaps.com/about/</ref>  ATAK has a plugin architecture which allows developers to add functionality.\n\nInitially created in 2010 by the [[Air Force Research Laboratory]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wpafb.af.mil/shared/media/document/|title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-05-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140520234009/http://www.wpafb.af.mil/shared/media/document/AFD-131008-023.pdf |archivedate=2014-05-20 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.cs.drexel.edu/~kfu22/you/docs/FP-MILCOM-Paper.pdf]{{dead link|date=December 2019}}</ref> and based on the NASA WorldWind Mobile codebase its development and deployment grew slowly then rapidly since 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fbo.gov/index?s=opportunity&